{"title_page": "Andrew", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox given name\n| name                 = Andrew\n| image                = Andreas San Giovanni in Laterano 2006-09-07.jpg\n| image_size           = \n| caption              = [[Andrew the Apostle|Saint Andrew]]\n| pronunciation        = {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u00e6|n|d|r|u\u02d0}}\n| gender               = [[Male]]\n| meaning              = manly and strong<ref name=\"etymonline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=Andrew |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |work=etymonline.com}}</ref><ref name=\"behind the name\">{{cite web |url=http://www.behindthename.com/name/andrew |title=Behind the Name: Meaning, Origin and History of the Name Andrew |author=Mike Campbell |work=Behind the Name}}</ref>\n| name day             = [[November 30]]\n| region               = [[Greece]]\n| languageorigin       = [[Greek language|Greek]]\n| seealso              = [[Ander]], [[Anders]], [[Andy (given name)|Andy]], [[Andre (given name)|Andre]], [[Andrei (given name)|Andrei]], [[Andrejs]], [[Andrzej (disambiguation)|Andrzej]], [[Andriy]], [[Andrea]], [[Andreas]], [[Andrey]], [[Andrej]], [[Andres (name)|Andres]]\n}}\n\n'''Andrew''' is the English form of a [[given name]] common in many countries. In the 1990s, it was among the top ten most popular names given to boys in [[List of countries where English is an official language|English-speaking countries]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.babycenter.com/babyname/names90.html |title=BabyCenter 1990s \u2013 Most Popular Names}}</ref>  \"Andrew\" is frequently shortened to \"Andy\" or \"Drew\". The word is derived from the {{lang-el|\u1f08\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1\u03c2}}, ''[[Andreas]]'',<ref name=\"urlOnline Etymology Dictionary\">{{cite web |url=http://etymonline.com/index.php?term=Andrew |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |format= |work= |accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref> itself related to {{lang-grc|\u1f00\u03bd\u03ae\u03c1/\u1f00\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2}} ''aner/andros'', \"man\" (as opposed to \"woman\"), thus meaning \"manly\" and, as consequence, \"brave\", \"strong\", \"courageous\", and \"warrior\". In the [[King James Version|King James Bible]], the Greek \"\u1f08\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1\u03c2\" is translated as Andrew.<ref name=\"urlBible Concordance: Andrew\">{{cite web |url=http://concordances.org/a/andrew.htm |title=Bible Concordance: Andrew |accessdate=2 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008063719/http://concordances.org/a/andrew.htm |archivedate=8 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Popularity ==\n\n=== Australia ===\nIn 2000, the name Andrew was the second most popular name in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.babynames.com.au/Search/search-categories-popular-list.asp?Year=1990&Gender=Boys |title=Popular names, 1990s |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061005221933/http://www.babynames.com.au/Search/search-categories-popular-list.asp?Year=1990&Gender=Boys |archivedate=October 5, 2006}}</ref> In 1999, it was the 19th most common name,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.babynames.com.au/Search/search-categories-popular-list.asp?Year=1980&Gender=Boys |title=Popular names, 1980s |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927173454/http://www.babynames.com.au/Search/search-categories-popular-list.asp?Year=1980&Gender=Boys |archivedate=September 27, 2006}}</ref> while in 1940, it was the 31st most common name.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.babynames.com.au/Search/search-categories-popular-list.asp?Year=1970&Gender=Boys |title=Popular names, 1970s |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061005221515/http://www.babynames.com.au/Search/search-categories-popular-list.asp?Year=1970&Gender=Boys |archivedate=October 5, 2006}}</ref> Andrew was the first most popular name given to boys in the Northern Territory in 2003 to 2015 and continuing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt.gov.au/justice/graphpages/bdm/popnames.shtml |title=Births, Deaths & Marriages (Most Popular Names) \u2013 Northern Territory Department of Justice \u2013 Australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312155853/http://www.nt.gov.au/justice/graphpages/bdm/popnames.shtml |archivedate=March 12, 2007}}</ref> In Victoria, Andrew was the first most popular name for a boy in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://baby2see.com/names/australian_baby_boys_names.html |title=Most Popular Boys Baby Names in Australia}}</ref>\n\n=== Canada ===\nAndrew was the 20th most popular name chosen for male infants in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todaysparent.com/pregnancybirth/becomingparent/article.jsp?content=20050617_144619_5504&page=1 |title=Top 100 Baby Names in Canada |publisher=Today's Parent |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904041213/http://www.todaysparent.com/pregnancybirth/becomingparent/article.jsp?content=20050617_144619_5504&page=1 |archivedate=2007-09-04}}</ref>\nAndrew was the 16th most popular name for infants in British Columbia in 2004,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vs.gov.bc.ca/babynames/baby2004.html |title=BC Vital Statistics Agency (2004) |publisher=British Columbia Ministry of Health |access-date=2007-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070427125603/http://www.vs.gov.bc.ca/babynames/baby2004.html |archive-date=2007-04-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the 17th most popular name in 2003,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vs.gov.bc.ca/babynames/baby2003.html |title=BC Vital Statistics Agency (2003) |publisher=British Columbia Ministry of Health |access-date=2007-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503162309/http://www.vs.gov.bc.ca/babynames/baby2003.html |archive-date=2007-05-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the 19th most popular name in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vs.gov.bc.ca/babynames/baby2002.html |title=BC Vital Statistics Agency (2002) |publisher=British Columbia Ministry of Health |access-date=2007-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503162355/http://www.vs.gov.bc.ca/babynames/baby2002.html |archive-date=2007-05-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2001, it was the 18th most common name.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vs.gov.bc.ca/babynames/baby2001.html |title=BC Vital Statistics Agency (2001) |publisher=British Columbia Ministry of Health |access-date=2007-04-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503162056/http://www.vs.gov.bc.ca/babynames/baby2001.html |archive-date=2007-05-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> From 1999 to 2003, Andrew was the sixth most often chosen name for a boy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://baby2see.com/names/canada_babynames.html |title=Most Popular Babies Names in Canada}}</ref>\n\n=== Europe ===\nIn the United Kingdom in 1974, Andrew was the fourth-most common name given to baby boys, and it was third in 1964. In Scotland, Andrew was the most popular name given to baby boys in 1993, with 1,099 boys given the name that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.babycenter.ca/pregnancy/naming/topnamespast/ |title=Popular baby names from the past}}</ref>\n\nIn Norway, with the spelling 'Andreas', the name has been the second-most common name given to boys of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ssb.no/navn/topp10/topp50/1990.html |title=Popular boy baby names 1990\u20131999}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Year\n! England & Wales\n! Ireland\n! Northern Ireland\n! Scotland\n! Norway\n! Poland\n|-\n| 2007 || 99th<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourbabynames.co.uk/ukpopular2007.php |title=Top Baby Names for Boys in England and Wales (2007)}}</ref> || * || * || * || *\n| 19th\n|-\n| 2006 || 97th<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thinkbabynames.com/popular/1/england/2006 |title=Top Baby Names for Boys in England and Wales (2006)}}</ref> || * || * || * || 6th<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ssb.no/en/befolkning/statistikker/navn/aar/2015-01-27?fane=tabell&sort=nummer&tabell=215683 |title=Statistics Norway}}<